V'''Monroe Curtis Beardsley''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u026a\u0259r|d|z|l|i}}; December 10, 1915 \u2013 September 18, 1985) was an [[American philosopher]] of art. He was born and raised in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], and educated at [[Yale University]] (B.A. 1936, Ph.D. 1939), where he received the [[John Addison Porter]] Prize. He taught at a number of colleges and universities, including [[Mount Holyoke College]] and Yale University, but most of his career was spent at [[Swarthmore College]] (22 years) and [[Temple University]] (16 years). His wife and occasional coauthor, Elizabeth Lane Beardsley, was also a philosopher at Temple.\u000a\u000aHis work in [[aesthetics]] is best known for its championing of the [[instrumentalism|instrumentalist]] theory of art and the concept of aesthetic experience. Beardsley was elected president of the American Society for Aesthetics in 1956. He also wrote an introductory text on aesthetics and edited a well-regarded survey anthology of philosophy.\u000a\u000aAmong [[Literary criticism|literary critics]], Beardsley is known for two essays written with [[William Kurtz Wimsatt, Jr.|W.K. Wimsatt]], "The [[Intentional Fallacy]]" and "The Affective Fallacy," both key texts of [[New Criticism]].  His works also include: ''Practical Logic'' (1950), ''Aesthetics'' (1958), and ''Aesthetics: A Short History'' (1966). He was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1976.<ref name=AAAS>{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780-2010: Chapter B|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterB.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=May 29, 2011}}</ref>\u000a\u000aHe and his wife were over-all series editors for Prentice-Hall's "Foundations of Philosophy," a series of textbooks on different fields within philosophy, written in most cases by leading scholars in those fields.\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a*[[American philosophy]]\u000a*[[List of American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* {{cite SEP |url-id=beardsley-aesthetics |title=Beardsley's Aesthetics |last=Wreen  |first=Michael|date=2005-09-13}}\u000a* Monroe C. Beardsley, [http://www.ditext.com/anka/beardsley/post.html "Postscript 1980-: Some Old Problems in New Perspectives,"] in ''Aesthetics: Problems in the Philosophy of Criticism'', 1st ed., 1958; 2d ed., 1981.\u000a* [http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-91923.html?from=../16/16-01400.html&from_nm=Roethke%2C%20Theodore American National Biography Online: Beardsley, Monroe C.]\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Beardsley, Monroe}}\u000a[[Category:1915 births]]\u000a[[Category:1985 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\u000a[[Category:American literary critics]]\u000a[[Category:Mount Holyoke College faculty]]\u000a[[Category:New Criticism]]\u000a[[Category:Writers from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of art]]\u000a[[Category:Swarthmore College faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Temple University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Yale University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\u000a\u000a\u000a{{US-philosopher-stub}}
